{
  "text": "There is evidence that symptoms of spinal cord compression appear after the cord has been reduced either by 30% in size or to a transverse area of less than 60 mm 2 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Ogino et al. also observed that the severity of the pathological changes in the spine of patients with CSM correlated significantly with the extent of compression [CITATION_3] . However, the transverse area of the spinal cord did not correlate well with the preoperative neurological status. The transverse area of the spinal cord was found to be the most significant factor in determining the response to surgery [CITATION_4] .",
